post_text:
Dear Classmates and Schoolmated: Due to Covid-19, and the fact that as of this date, we can not congregate in large numbers, the Caldwell HS All-Alumni Dinner, scheduled for July 25, 2020, has been canceled. We deeply regret the need to make this decision and hope that you will mark your calendar now for Saturday, July 31, 2021. Thank you for your continuing interest in our hometown and high school. Please reply to this page is you have questions.

Sincerely,
Caldwell HS All-Alumni Committee: Vicki Snyder, Sharon McConnell, Faith Nichols, Cathy Bond, Charlotte Norris, Beth Saling

Reply Reply All Forward

post_text: Happy New Year to CHS grads and friends. 2020 will be a year of major change either way you look at it. But change is what makes us wake up. We have so much yet too often we fail to be grateful for the important things. Our family and friends. In a few months, the CHS All Alumni Reunion will return and provide us the opportunity to chat with people who we know, I mean really know. We share roots. We knew each other's parents and even grandparents. We may have gone to the same church; we sure went to the same school. Please plan to attend this year's reunion and in the meantime, post on this page your thought, pictures and feeling about our hometown, Caldwell.

shared_text:
Ina Garten
November 7, 2019 at 3:00 PM ·

Nora Ephron once joked that whenever you went to a dinner party in New York in the 80s, Chicken Marbella was on the menu. Originally published in the Silver Palate Cookbook, it was chicken roasted with prunes, brown sugar, olives, capers, and garlic. I decided to update the classic recipe with even more garlic and a little less brown sugar, and now happily it's one of my favorite make-ahead recipes for a dinner party. I assemble the whole thing the night before and just pop it in the oven before dinner! That's my kind of recipe!

https://barefootcontessa.com/recipes/chicken-marbella-updated
text:
Ina Garten
November 7, 2019 at 3:00 PM ·

Nora Ephron once joked that whenever you went to a dinner party in New York in the 80s, Chicken Marbella was on the menu. Originally published in the Silver Palate Cookbook, it was chicken roasted with prunes, brown sugar, olives, capers, and garlic. I decided to update the classic recipe with even more garlic and a little less brown sugar, and now happily it's one of my favorite make-ahead recipes for a dinner party. I assemble the whole thing the night before and just pop it in the oven before dinner! That's my kind of recipe!
